1ï¸âƒ£ Palindrome Check
ğŸ”¹ Problem

Check whether a given string is a palindrome
(A string that reads the same forward and backward)

ğŸ§  Python Code (2 lines)
s = "madam"
print(s == s[::-1])

ğŸ“– Explanation

s[::-1] creates the reversed version of the string.

We compare the original string with its reverse.

If both are equal â†’ it is a palindrome.

â±ï¸ Interview Insight

Time Complexity: O(n)

Space Complexity: O(n) (new reversed string)

ğŸ¤ How to Explain in Interview

â€œI reverse the string using slicing and compare it with the original to check for palindrome.â€

2ï¸âƒ£ String Reverse
ğŸ”¹ Problem

Reverse a given string.

ğŸ§  Python Code (1 line)
s = "hello"
print(s[::-1])

ğŸ“– Explanation

[::-1] tells Python to:

Start from the end

Move backward one step at a time

It returns a new reversed string.

â±ï¸ Interview Insight

Time Complexity: O(n)

Space Complexity: O(n)

ğŸ¤ How to Explain in Interview

â€œPython slicing allows reversing a string in a single readable line.â€

ğŸ¤ FAANG Interview Round (Professional Answers)

Q1. What is a palindrome?
A: A string that remains the same when reversed.

Q2. Can palindrome be checked without reversing?
A: Yes, using two pointers from start and end.

Q3. Are strings mutable in Python?
A: No, strings are immutable.

Q4. Why slicing is popular in interviews?
A: It shows clarity and Python proficiency.
